A4: The L1 Solar Shield: Diffractive vs. Dispersive Models

Physics of Solar Radiation Management

Required Reduction: 1.7% of solar constant (340 W/m²) = 5.78 W/m² reduction
Equivalent: Blocking ~1.8×10¹⁵ watts globally

Dispersive Model (Micro-shade Cloud)

Design Parameters:

· Individual shades: 0.5 m diameter, 0.1 g each (silicone/silica)
· Total number: 16 trillion units
· Total mass: 1.6 million tons
· Station-keeping: Solar radiation pressure for positioning

Advantages:

· Gradual deployment
· Fail-safe (individual unit failure negligible)
· Manufacturing possible from lunar/asteroid materials

Challenges:

· Collision probability: 10⁻⁷/year/unit
· Long-term stability requires active control

Diffractive Model (Fresnel Zone Plate)

Design:

· Single structure: 1000 km diameter
· Mass: 200,000 tons (graphene-aluminum composite)
· Thickness: 1 micron
· Diffraction angle: 0.5° deflection

Advantages:

· Single control system
· Predictable performance
· No debris generation

Challenges:

· Single-point failure risk
· Deployment complexity
· Requires in-space manufacturing

Orbital Mechanics & Station-Keeping

L1 Location: 1.5×10⁶ km from Earth (0.01 AU)
Orbital period: 6 months around L1 halo orbit
Delta-V requirement: 50 m/s/year for station-keeping
Lagrange point stability: L1 is unstable (requires active control)

Deployment Timeline:

1. Robotic factory at LEO (Years 1-5)
2. Mass driver from Moon supplies material (Years 6-10)
3. Gradual shield assembly (Years 11-20)
4. Full operation (Year 21+)

Climate Impact Modeling:

· 1% reduction → -1.2°C global mean temperature
· Latitudinal distribution: Uniform cooling
· Precipitation impact: <2% change in hydrological cycle
· Risk mitigation: Reversible within 1 year (shield removal)

